01:41:29,050 --> 01:41:33,345
well, then.. Then that's my mission.

1199
01:41:35,390 --> 01:41:36,974
You want to leave?

1200
01:41:37,058 --> 01:41:40,102
You want to go off and fight the war?

1201
01:41:42,981 --> 01:41:44,440
All right.

1202
01:41:45,775 --> 01:41:48,319
All right, I won't stop you.

1203
01:41:48,403 --> 01:41:50,988
I'll even put in the paperwork.

1204
01:41:52,949 --> 01:41:57,328
I just know that every man I kill,
the farther away from home I feel.

1205
01:43:22,539 --> 01:43:24,123
By memories

1206
01:43:25,458 --> 01:43:27,501
Of the days gone by

1207
01:43:29,337 --> 01:43:31,130
In my solitude

1208
01:43:32,048 --> 01:43:34,508
You taunt me

1209
01:43:34,592 --> 01:43:38,137
With memories that never die

1210
01:43:39,347 --> 01:43:41,807
I sit in my chair

1211
01:43:41,891 --> 01:43:44,101
Filled with despair

1212
01:43:44,185 --> 01:43:46,019
There's no one

1213
01:43:46,104 --> 01:43:48,522
Could be so sad

1214
01:43:49,399 --> 01:43:51,442
With gloom everywhere

1215
01:43:51,526 --> 01:43:54,153
I sit and I stare..

1216
01:44:08,042 --> 01:44:10,127
Half track! Cover!

1217
01:44:25,810 --> 01:44:29,354
Who's doing the shooting?
Who's doing the shooting?

1218
01:44:50,251 --> 01:44:52,628
Get ready to move on their left flank!
Take their left flank!

1219
01:44:52,712 --> 01:44:55,589
Hold on and make sure they're down!

1220
01:45:16,736 --> 01:45:19,363
101 st! We're coming out!

1221
01:45:26,788 --> 01:45:29,748
That was a recon element, 2nd SS.

1222
01:45:31,084 --> 01:45:34,670
We've been expecting a probe.
That must have been it.

1223
01:45:36,548 --> 01:45:39,967
Captain Miller,
Charlie Company, 2nd Rangers.

1224
01:45:40,051 --> 01:45:42,135
Corporal Henderson,
Easy Company, 501 st.

1225
01:45:42,220 --> 01:45:43,720
Ryan. First of the 506th.

1226
01:45:43,805 --> 01:45:46,181
PFC Toynbe, Third of the 506th.

1227
01:45:46,266 --> 01:45:48,225
James Francis Ryan?

1228
01:45:48,309 --> 01:45:50,811
Yes, sir. How'd you guess that?

1229
01:46:02,574 --> 01:46:05,534
Looks like you guys got hit pretty hard.

1230
01:46:05,618 --> 01:46:09,162
Yes, sir. Small unit action.

1231
01:46:11,583 --> 01:46:15,168
They came in,
and beat the hell out of us with 88s.

1232
01:46:21,384 --> 01:46:24,928
Tell you what, sir, if you're our relief,
I'm gonna file a complaint.

1233
01:46:25,013 --> 01:46:26,972
I wouldn't blame you.

1234
01:46:27,724 --> 01:46:29,474
Who's your CO?

1235
01:46:31,060 --> 01:46:33,854
It would have been
Captain Jennings, sir.

1236
01:46:33,938 --> 01:46:38,400
I'm afraid the best we can muster up
right now is a corporal.

1237
01:46:38,484 --> 01:46:41,028
So, what are you guys all about?

1238
01:46:41,613 --> 01:46:44,114
We're here for him. Ryan.

1239
01:46:45,450 --> 01:46:46,908
Me, sir?

1240
01:46:56,252 --> 01:46:58,629
James Francis Ryan of Iowa?

1241
01:46:59,464 --> 01:47:02,924
Yes, sir.
Payton, Iowa, that's correct, but..

1242
01:47:03,009 --> 01:47:05,010
What is this about?

1243
01:47:06,846 --> 01:47:09,640
Your brothers were killed in combat.

1244
01:47:16,439 --> 01:47:18,065
Which ones?

1245
01:47:20,985 --> 01:47:22,486
All of them.

1246
01:47:32,372 --> 01:47:33,955
On the level?

1247
01:47:35,375 --> 01:47:37,334
Yeah. I'm afraid so.

1248
01:47:40,088 --> 01:47:42,047
You might want to take
some time with this.

1249
01:47:42,131 --> 01:47:45,175
If there's someplace
you want to go and..

1250
01:47:54,185 --> 01:47:57,104
- What's this all about?
- Ryan lost his brothers.

1251
01:47:57,188 --> 01:47:59,564
- Which one?
- All of them.

1252
01:48:04,529 --> 01:48:05,904
You..

1253
01:48:08,533 --> 01:48:11,827
You came all the way
out here to tell me that?

1254
01:48:13,538 --> 01:48:15,706
Well, you're going home.

1255
01:48:17,208 --> 01:48:19,793
Our orders are to bring you back.

1256
01:48:23,089 --> 01:48:24,715
Bring me back?

1257
01:48:27,093 --> 01:48:30,595
Corporal Henderson, I don't mean
to leave you even more shorthanded,

1258
01:48:30,680 --> 01:48:32,013
but orders are orders.

1259
01:48:32,098 --> 01:48:34,933
Any communication about when
you're going to be relieved up here?

1260
01:48:35,059 --> 01:48:36,268
Sir, there's no way to tell. I mean,

1261
01:48:36,394 --> 01:48:37,936
we have no idea
what's happening south of us.

1262
01:48:38,020 --> 01:48:39,354
I have my orders, too, sir.

1263
01:48:39,439 --> 01:48:41,356
They don't include me
abandoning my post.

1264
01:48:41,441 --> 01:48:44,359
I understand that,
but this changes things.

1265
01:48:44,444 --> 01:48:46,778
I don't see that it does, sir.

1266
01:48:48,406 --> 01:48:51,450
The Chief of Staff
for the United States Army says it does.

1267
01:48:51,534 --> 01:48:54,369
Sir, our orders are to hold
this bridge at all cost.

1268
01:48:54,454 --> 01:48:56,955
Now, our planes in the 82nd
have taken out every bridge

1269
01:48:57,081 --> 01:48:59,040
across the Merderet
with the exception of two.

1270
01:48:59,125 --> 01:49:00,709
One at Valognes and this one here.

1271
01:49:00,793 --> 01:49:02,043
We let the Germans take them,

1272
01:49:02,128 --> 01:49:03,712
we're gonna lose our foothold
and have to displace.

1273
01:49:03,796 --> 01:49:07,299
Private, your outfit wants to stay,
that's one thing.

1274
01:49:07,383 --> 01:49:08,467
But your party's over here.

1275
01:49:08,551 --> 01:49:10,719
Sir, I can't leave
until at least reinforcements..

1276
01:49:10,803 --> 01:49:13,221
You got three minutes
to gather your gear.

1277
01:49:13,306 --> 01:49:15,390
Sir, what about them?
I mean, there's barely hardly enough..

1278
01:49:15,475 --> 01:49:16,975
Hey, asshole!

1279
01:49:17,727 --> 01:49:21,605
Two of our guys already died
trying to find you, all right?

1280
01:49:26,652 --> 01:49:29,321
- Sir?
- That's right.

1281
01:49:39,207 --> 01:49:43,710
- What were their names?
- Irwin Wade and Adrian Caparzo.

1282
01:49:45,671 --> 01:49:47,214
Wade and..

1283
01:49:48,716 --> 01:49:50,175
Caparzo.

1284
01:50:02,563 --> 01:50:04,981
It doesn't make any sense.

1285
01:50:07,068 --> 01:50:11,321
It doesn't make sense, sir.
Why? Why do I deserve to go?

1286
01:50:11,405 --> 01:50:15,575
Why not any of these guys?
They all fought just as hard as me!

1287
01:50:19,205 --> 01:50:22,290
Is that what they're
supposed to tell your mother

1288
01:50:22,375 --> 01:50:25,710
when they send her another
folded American flag?

1289
01:50:32,927 --> 01:50:35,345
Tell her that when you found me,

1290
01:50:35,429 --> 01:50:39,099
I was here and I was
with the only brothers that I have left,

1291
01:50:39,225 --> 01:50:42,435
and that there's no way
I was gonna desert them.

1292
01:50:43,604 --> 01:50:45,772
I think she'll understand that.

1293
01:50:45,898 --> 01:50:48,859
There's no way I'm leaving this bridge.

1294
01:51:31,861 --> 01:51:33,945
What are your orders?

1295
01:51:35,781 --> 01:51:39,117
Sergeant, we have crossed
some strange boundary here.

1296
01:51:40,119 --> 01:51:42,704
The world has taken a turn
for the surreal.

1297
01:51:42,788 --> 01:51:45,624
Clearly, but the question still stands.

1298
01:51:46,292 --> 01:51:49,294
I don't know. What do you think?

1299
01:51:50,338 --> 01:51:53,131
You don't want to know what I think.

1300
01:51:55,009 --> 01:51:56,676
No, Mike, I do.

1301
01:51:58,387 --> 01:52:01,681
Well, part of me thinks the kid's right.

1302
01:52:01,807 --> 01:52:04,309
What's he done to deserve this?

1303
01:52:04,393 --> 01:52:08,355
He wants to stay here, fine,
let's leave him and go home.

1304
01:52:09,649 --> 01:52:10,899
Yeah.

1305
01:52:11,484 --> 01:52:16,571
But another part of me thinks
what if, by some miracle, we stay

1306
01:52:16,656 --> 01:52:19,324
and actually make it out of here?

1307
01:52:20,201 --> 01:52:23,828
Someday we might look back on this
and decide that

1308
01:52:23,913 --> 01:52:27,332
saving Private Ryan
was the one decent thing

1309
01:52:27,416 --> 01:52:30,335
we were able to pull out of this whole

1310
01:52:30,419 --> 01:52:32,545
God-awful, shitty mess.

1311
01:52:34,215 --> 01:52:36,716
That's what I was thinking, sir.

1312
01:52:37,885 --> 01:52:40,053
Like you said, Captain,

1313
01:52:41,847 --> 01:52:43,556
we do that,

1314
01:52:44,016 --> 01:52:46,851
we all earn the right to go home.

1315
01:52:49,689 --> 01:52:51,231
Oh, brother.

1316
01:52:54,694 --> 01:52:57,028
This is everything.

1317
01:52:57,738 --> 01:53:03,368
You got the two 30-calibre machine
guns, 17 grenades, 11 Hawkins mines.

1318
01:53:04,120 --> 01:53:07,455
You got the two bazookas,
but they only got eight rounds left,

1319
01:53:07,540 --> 01:53:09,749
and assorted small arms.

1320
01:53:09,875 --> 01:53:13,336
We had a 60 mortar
but an arty round took it out.

1321
01:53:13,421 --> 01:53:16,089
Might as well be spit wads
if they roll on us with tanks.

1322
01:53:16,215 --> 01:53:19,426
- Which they're sure to do.
- What are you thinking, sir?

1323
01:53:19,552 --> 01:53:24,139
Well, I'm thinking they're going to try
to whip around the flanks.

1324
01:53:28,728 --> 01:53:30,979
Unless we can draw
them up this main road here

1325
01:53:31,063 --> 01:53:32,188
in between these buildings

1326
01:53:32,273 --> 01:53:36,234
where all the rubble makes
a bit of a bottleneck.

1327
01:53:36,318 --> 01:53:38,361
- Disable 'em?
- If we can.

1328
01:53:38,446 --> 01:53:40,030
Make that tank a 60-ton roadblock.

1329
01:53:40,114 --> 01:53:41,948
We do that, we got
a fighting chance at their flanks.

1330
01:53:42,074 --> 01:53:44,451
Yes, sir that's good. Split them up.
Don't let them mass anywhere.

1331
01:53:44,577 --> 01:53:47,495
Hit them hard as we can, one-on-one,
and fall back to the bridge.

1332
01:53:47,580 --> 01:53:49,789
Machine gun on the move down here,
and number two up high somewhere

1333
01:53:49,915 --> 01:53:51,916
to piss a little bad news down
on their heads.

1334
01:53:52,001 --> 01:53:54,252
That would be the idea.

1335
01:53:54,795 --> 01:53:56,254
Jackson.

1336
01:53:56,922 --> 01:53:59,174
If we can, I'd like to get you up
in that bell tower.

1337
01:53:59,258 --> 01:54:00,768
Yes, sir.

1338
01:54:00,781 --> 01:54:02,302
Give you a little
company if you need it.

1339
01:54:02,428 --> 01:54:04,429
Yes, sir. Some company couldn't hurt.

1340
01:54:04,513 --> 01:54:08,558
I'd say a .30 with about
1,000 rounds would be okay.

1341
01:54:08,642 --> 01:54:10,685
Parker, job opportunity.

1342
01:54:10,770 --> 01:54:12,771
Yeah. Well, it's not the worst idea
ever, Captain.

1343
01:54:12,855 --> 01:54:14,439
It's just that everything depends
on getting the tank

1344
01:54:14,523 --> 01:54:16,608
down this main road for us
to knock out, right?

1345
01:54:16,776 --> 01:54:19,778
So how the hell do you
plan on doing that?

1346
01:54:20,279 --> 01:54:23,198
Reiben's right. As our esteemed
colleague from the Airborne pointed out,

1347
01:54:23,282 --> 01:54:25,575
what we got here are
a bunch of spit wads,

1348
01:54:25,659 --> 01:54:29,496
so how do we stop the tank
if we get it to commit?

1349
01:54:29,622 --> 01:54:31,998
Give it a rabbit to chase.

1350
01:54:32,124 --> 01:54:35,251
We could hit the tank in the tracks.

1351
01:54:35,336 --> 01:54:37,462
Yeah, but with what?

1352
01:54:39,131 --> 01:54:42,967
- Well, we could try a sticky bomb.
- Sticky bomb, sir?

1353
01:54:44,178 --> 01:54:48,014
- Sir, are you making that up?
- No. It's in the field manual.

1354
01:54:48,140 --> 01:54:49,974
You check it out if you want to.

1355
01:54:50,059 --> 01:54:52,143
We seem to be out of field manuals, sir.

1356
01:54:52,228 --> 01:54:54,145
Perhaps you can enlighten us?

1357
01:54:54,230 --> 01:54:55,688
All right, you have
some demolition, don't you?

1358
01:54:55,815 --> 01:54:57,732
Some TNT or some composition B?

1359
01:54:57,817 --> 01:54:59,526
Yeah, that, sir, is the one thing
we got plenty of.

1360
01:54:59,652 --> 01:55:02,278
I got that bridge wired with enough
composition B to blow it twice.

1361
01:55:02,363 --> 01:55:04,364
All right. You can spare some, then.

1362
01:55:04,490 --> 01:55:07,700
You take a standard-issue GI sock,

1363
01:55:07,827 --> 01:55:10,912
cram it with as much
comp B as it can hold,

1364
01:55:10,996 --> 01:55:13,456
rig up a simple fuse,

1365
01:55:13,541 --> 01:55:16,084
then you coat the whole thing
with axle grease.

1366
01:55:16,168 --> 01:55:20,672
That way, when you throw it,
it should stick. It's a bomb that sticks.

1367
01:55:20,756 --> 01:55:22,382
It's a sticky bomb.

1368
01:55:22,508 --> 01:55:24,884
You come up with a better way
to knock the tracks off a tank,

1369
01:55:25,010 --> 01:55:26,594
I'm all ears.

1370
01:55:26,679 --> 01:55:30,223
This is good.
Now we got to surrender our socks.

1371
01:55:44,697 --> 01:55:46,197
Haul away.

1372
01:56:00,212 --> 01:56:04,132
All right, select the field of fire.
Crossfire with the one in the bell tower.

1373
01:56:04,216 --> 01:56:07,552
All right, I can cover
12 to nine from here.

1374
01:56:10,764 --> 01:56:12,891
- Easy!
- I got her!

1375
01:56:47,259 --> 01:56:49,093
Here are the mines.

1376
01:57:00,022 --> 01:57:02,440
For being the best we can do,

1377
01:57:02,524 --> 01:57:06,527
that forward machine gun
is not in a terrible firing position.

1378
01:57:09,198 --> 01:57:11,699
And this position right here,

1379
01:57:13,786 --> 01:57:15,370
this is the Alamo.

1380
01:57:15,955 --> 01:57:19,624
They push us back this far,
last man alive blows the bridge.

1381
01:57:19,708 --> 01:57:21,751
We only got a 30-second delay
on that fuse,

1382
01:57:21,835 --> 01:57:23,878
so let everyone know that
if you are that last man

1383
01:57:23,963 --> 01:57:28,049
you better hurry your ass off,
or you're not going to be alive long.

1384
01:57:28,133 --> 01:57:31,552
Captain? Where am I during all this?

1385
01:57:32,471 --> 01:57:34,430
Never more than
two feet away from me,

1386
01:57:34,515 --> 01:57:36,724
and that's not negotiable.

1387
01:57:37,851 --> 01:57:40,311
I'll get some ammo. Come on.

1388
01:57:43,315 --> 01:57:44,607
- Hey, Upham.
- Yes.

1389
01:57:44,692 --> 01:57:46,567
- Listen to me, all right?
- Yeah.

1390
01:57:46,652 --> 01:57:48,194
- You're listening?
- Yes.

1391
01:57:48,320 --> 01:57:50,363
All right, we're gonna be displacing

1392
01:57:50,489 --> 01:57:52,073
and falling back like crazy
sons of bitches.

1393
01:57:52,157 --> 01:57:53,241
Right up there.

1394
01:57:53,325 --> 01:57:56,786
So you got to be Johnny on the spot
with the ammo, or we're dead.

1395
01:57:56,870 --> 01:57:58,579
- Right.
- You understand that?

1396
01:57:58,664 --> 01:58:00,957
- Johnny on the spot.
- Yeah.

1397
01:58:01,041 --> 01:58:04,168
- You all right?
- Yeah. Yes.

1398
01:58:04,503 --> 01:58:05,753
You know, when we were
shipping out of England

1399
01:58:05,838 --> 01:58:07,797
the supply sergeant was handing
out cartons of cigarettes,

1400
01:58:07,881 --> 01:58:11,009
and I said "No, thank you,
I don't smoke."

1401
01:58:12,011 --> 01:58:13,594
"I don't smoke."

1402
01:58:15,431 --> 01:58:18,391
- Quite a situation, huh?
- Unbelievable.

1403
01:58:19,727 --> 01:58:25,273
Here. Fucked up beyond
all recognition, right?

1404
01:58:25,733 --> 01:58:27,608
You got that right.

1405
01:58:29,862 --> 01:58:31,237
FUBAR.

1406
01:58:33,574 --> 01:58:34,615
Ouch.

1407
01:58:34,908 --> 01:58:36,534
- Yeah, well..
- FUBAR.

1408
01:58:36,618 --> 01:58:39,120
It's going to be a real show, huh?

1409
01:58:39,204 --> 01:58:41,122
Yeah. Okay.

1410
01:58:47,379 --> 01:58:49,047
Take it easy.

1411
01:58:50,215 --> 01:58:51,674
FUBAR.

1412
01:59:29,588 --> 01:59:33,925
- Who's that singing, sir?
- Edith Piaf.

1413
01:59:36,345 --> 01:59:38,888
What's she so upset about?

1414
01:59:39,723 --> 01:59:41,265
Her lover left her,

1415
01:59:41,392 --> 01:59:44,852
but she still sees his face
everywhere she goes.

1416
01:59:46,021 --> 01:59:47,939
That would do it.

1417
02:00:17,219 --> 02:00:20,179
"Even life itself only represents you."

1418
02:00:23,308 --> 02:00:25,893
"Sometimes I dream
that I'm in your arms."

1419
02:00:25,978 --> 02:00:28,396
What was that part?
She sang that before.

1420
02:00:28,480 --> 02:00:30,857
- The chorus. It's the chorus.
- The chorus.

1421
02:00:31,608 --> 02:00:34,235
"And you speak softly in my ear"

1422
02:00:36,113 --> 02:00:38,531
"and you say things"

1423
02:00:38,615 --> 02:00:41,033
"that make my eyes close."

1424
02:00:43,370 --> 02:00:45,455
"And I find that marvellous."

1425
02:00:45,539 --> 02:00:48,166
- Again, Upham..
- Yes.

1426
02:00:48,876 --> 02:00:53,504
To be honest with you,
I find myself curiously aroused by you.

1427
02:00:54,381 --> 02:00:57,884
- Marvellous.
- No, it's really a melancholy song.

1428
02:00:58,010 --> 02:01:01,679
At the beginning of the song, she says,
"And then one day, you left."

1429
02:01:01,805 --> 02:01:05,808
"You left me, and I've been
desperate ever since."

1430
02:01:05,893 --> 02:01:09,061
"I see you all over the sky,
I see you all over the Earth."

1431
02:01:09,188 --> 02:01:10,813
Jesus, Upham,
any more songs like this,

1432
02:01:10,898 --> 02:01:12,607
the krauts aren't going
to have to shoot me.

1433
02:01:12,691 --> 02:01:15,526
I'm just going to slit my own wrists.

1434
02:01:15,652 --> 02:01:18,321
You know,
you're a strange bird, Upham.

1435
02:01:18,405 --> 02:01:20,281
Sorry, it's Edith, you know.

1436
02:01:20,365 --> 02:01:22,366
You know what
that song reminds me of?

1437
02:01:22,493 --> 02:01:25,161
It reminds me of Mrs Rachel Troubowitz
and what she said to me

1438
